%description:
TCP Fast Open (RFC 7413) client-side opt-in is per-connection, like Linux's
MSG_FASTOPEN/TCP_FASTOPEN_CONNECT -- NOT "attach a cached cookie to every SYN
to a destination that happens to have one cached because the module-wide
fastopenClientEnabled parameter is on". Connection 1 (port 1000,
fastOpen=true) primes the client's cookie cache for the server address, same
as tcp_fastopen_1.test. Connection 2 (port 1001) then does a PLAIN
connect() (fastOpen2=false) to the same destination. Even though a cookie is
cached and fastopenClientEnabled is true module-wide, connection 2's SYN
must NOT carry a Fast Open option at all, because this connection's own
open() call never opted in.

Falsification: before the fastopenRequested fix, writeHeaderOptions()'s
client-side cookie-append block was gated only on state->fastopenClientEnabled
plus "is a cookie cached for this destination" -- with no way to see that
THIS connection's own connect() call asked for it. Under that gate,
connection 2's SYN would carry "FastOpen(cookieLen=8)" here, a wire-level
divergence from Linux (which never attaches TFO data to a connect() that
didn't request it). The single assertion below (a plain "S 126000:..." line
with no Option(s) FastOpen suffix) would fail -- the real (buggy) output
included the FastOpen option -- if that gate regressed.

%inifile: omnetpp.ini
[General]
record-vector-results = false
ned-path = .;../../../../src;../../lib

network = inet.test.moduletest.lib.TcpTestNet1

cmdenv-event-banners=false
cmdenv-express-mode=false
cmdenv-log-prefix="[%c]: "

*.testing=false
*.tcptester.script=""

*.cli_app.localAddress="10.0.0.1"
*.cli_app.localPort=1000
*.cli_app.connectAddress="10.0.0.2"
*.cli_app.connectPort=2000
*.cli_app.active=true
*.cli_app.tOpen=0s
*.cli_app.tSend=-1s
*.cli_app.sendBytes=0B
*.cli_app.tClose=-1s
*.cli_app.sendScript=""
*.cli_app.fastOpen=true
*.cli_app.active2=true
*.cli_app.tOpen2=0.5s
*.cli_app.localPort2=1001
*.cli_app.tSend2=-1s
*.cli_app.sendBytes2=0B
*.cli_app.fastOpen2=false

*.srv_app.localAddress="10.0.0.2"
*.srv_app.localPort=2000
*.srv_app.connectAddress="10.0.0.1"
*.srv_app.connectPort=1000
*.srv_app.active=false
*.srv_app.tOpen=0s
*.srv_app.tSend=-1s
*.srv_app.sendBytes=0B
*.srv_app.tClose=-1s
*.srv_app.sendScript=""
*.srv_app.active2=false
*.srv_app.tOpen2=0.5s
*.srv_app.localPort2=2000

*.*_tcp.sackSupport = false
*.*_tcp.windowScalingSupport = false
*.*_tcp.timestampSupport = false
*.*_tcp.mss = 1000
*.*_tcp.tcpAlgorithmClass = "TcpReno"

*.cli_tcp.fastopenClientEnabled = true
*.srv_tcp.fastopenServerEnabled = true
*.srv_tcp.fastopenLenientCookieValidation = false

include ../../lib/tcp-legacy.ini

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: postrun.pl
open FILE, '<test.out';
while($sor = <FILE>)
{
    if ($sor =~ /^\[testing\]: (.*)$/)
    {
        print "$1\n";
    }
}
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command:  perl ./postrun.pl
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Connection 1: bare cookie-request SYN, learned by the client (primes the cache), same as tcp_fastopen_1.test.
%contains: postrun-command(1).out
[0.001 A001] A.1000 > B.2000: S 0:0(0) win 7504   Option(s): MaxSegSize NOP NOP FastOpen(cookieLen=0)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains: postrun-command(1).out
[0.003 B001] A.1000 < B.2000: A S 500:500(0) ack 1 win 7504   Option(s): MaxSegSize NOP NOP FastOpen(cookieLen=8)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Connection 2: plain connect() (fastOpen2=false) to the same destination -- despite the
%# cached cookie and fastopenClientEnabled being on module-wide, this SYN must carry no
%# Fast Open option at all. The line is pinned end-to-end (through the trailing newline
%# into the next line's start) so a regression that appends " NOP NOP FastOpen(...)"
%# after "MaxSegSize" would break this exact contiguous match, not just get missed by
%# a loose substring check.
%contains: postrun-command(1).out
[0.501 A003] A.1001 > B.2000: S 125000:125000(0) win 7504   Option(s): MaxSegSize
srv_tcp: LISTEN --> SYN_RCVD  (on RCV_SYN)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
